summary.seg: This manuscript contains epigrams and brief fragments from the works of the ancient poet Callimachus with annotations on many of his works by Thomas Stanley (1625-1678), along with some notes regarding the content of the Chaldaian Oracles. Stanley was a poet, historian of philosophy and editor and translator of classical Greek texts. He left such annotations on a number of classical authors, but appears to have paid particular attention to Callimachus. The eminent classicist Richard Bentley (1662-1742) was accused in an anonymous pamphlet of using Stanley's notes without attribution (A Short Account of Dr. Bentley's Humanity and Justice to those Authors who have written before him, with an honest Vindication of Thomas Stanley, Esq., and his Notes on Callimachos (London 1699)).

support.material: Western paper, folded in octavo. Watermark: Foolscap ( c. 90 c. 50 ) at the top of the gutter, comparable but not identical to Heawood 1974.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript has been paginated with the numbers i-xl + 1-218 in Arabic and Roman numerals, in black ink (Arabic numerals) and pencil (Roman numerals). Numerals in ink appear on both recto and verso in the upper outer corner, numerals in pencil on recto only.
supportDesc.collation: The collation could not be determined.
supportDesc.condition: There is slight water staining and occasional areas of dirt.

layoutDesc.layout:
A single column of 13-21 lines. 100 65
Margins are ruled in red ink.

handNote.p: The manuscript was copied by Thomas Stanley, the Greek text in a western European mixed minuscule.

additions.p: The name of Dorothy Stanley, Thomas's wife, appears p. iii, probably as a dedication. Thomas Stanley has added a poem in English on p. v.
There are some brief annotations on p. i.
A poem in English, in pencil, has been added to pp. 208-209 and a poem in Greek on p. 216.

binding.p: 17th-century full leather binding over couched-laminate boards. There is decorative blind tooling on the boards and the edges, and gold tooling on the rebacked spine. The title Notae in Callimachi is tooled in gold on a red label on the spine, and the classmark appears on patches. The edges of the leaves have been painted green.
binding.condition: The spine has been rebacked. Some of the leather covering material has been lost from the head of the spine.

history.origin: The manuscript was written by the poet and scholar Thomas Stanley (1625-1678) Stanley, Thomas, 1625-1678 at some time between 1639 and 1675.
history.provenance: Stanley's annotations were reportedly used by the classical scholar Richard Bentley (1662-1742) Bentley, Richard, 1662-1742 (A Short Account of Dr. Bentley's Humanity and Justice to those Authors who have written before him, with an honest Vindication of Thomas Stanley, Esq., and his Notes on Callimachos (London 1699)).
